					<h2>Culture, Stereotypes, and Identities found in:<br><center>Movies & Books</center></h2>
				</div>
					<p>To what extent is our identity influenced by our family and community? How do stereotypes and prejudice affect who we think we are? How can stereotypes affect our sense of pride, security, and independence?</p>
					
					<p>The literary works include movies and books created by professionals in the field of literature. These writers talk about culture, stereotypes and peoples identities. The movies and books I address include,  "The Piano Lesson" by August Wilson, "Smoke Signals" by Sherman Alexie", "The House on Mango Street" by Sandra Cisernos and "M. Butterfly" by David Henry Hwang.
					Several Minority groups have had an extremely hard time in America and racial discrimination continues on today. I would like to address these issues in a moderate way, and again I wish to not offend anyone as this is purely academic.
		
					</p>
					
					<br>
					
					<h3>Smoke Signals</h3>
					<p>
					<br>The movie "Smoke Signals gives us a forecast into the modern day Native American world.
					It is a fast paced emotional and hysterical film, which was very enjoyable to watch. 
					Written by a Native American, Sherman Alexie, the cast follows and is entirely Native American as well.
					In the movie, "Smoke Signals" there were several typical stereotypes of Native Americans.
					<br><br>Here are a list of some of the stereotypes portrayed in the movie:
					<ul>
						<li>The stereotype that they live in teepees</li>
						<li>That they are addicted to alcohol and drugs.</li>
						<li>Spiritually connected to nature and intuitively know their culture and history</li>
						<li>Get assistance through casinos</li>
						<li>Live on reservations</li>
						<li>Lack an education</li>
					</ul>
					</p>
					<p>
						If the film does not specifically show individuals drunk, there are many references emphasizing it. Not only does the film support these stereotypes, but it seems to easily make fun of the Native American culture. For instance, during the scene when Victor and Thomas were on the bus to Arizona, Victor tells Thomas to stop acting like he is some type of “medicine man” and begins teaching him how to be “a true Indian.” Victor says to be “Indian” you have to have a certain facial expression: “like you are warriors or just came from a buffalo hunt.” The idea of storytelling or oral traditions is also an important factor in the movie.
						<br>The audience continually hears Thomas telling stories. It is not necessarily the story telling that is found funny, it is the way Thomas tells the stories; he acts like he is some kind of wise, astute man (as said before, like a medicine man). Overall, the movie seems to support many stereotypes of present day Native Americans.
