					<center>(Sherman Alexie)</center>
					</p>
					
					
					<h3>The Piano Lesson</h3>
					<p>Produced by August Wilson, an American Playright.</p>
					<p>The Piano Lesson was a great lesson about African American culture. It is also a movie about self identities and how people portray themselves.
					The piano in the play represented the family’s history. The family’s history was carved into the piano and their great grandmother and grandfather were traded for it. Their father even died while he was trying to retrieve the piano from the old slaveowner Sutter’s house. The piano also symbolizes slavery as well, and allows the family to grow stronger based on what happened in their past. The piano lesson had a hidden message that consists of the importance beyond material concerns, rather than a historical legacy. 
					The Piano Lesson conveys a message of learning as well and figuring out your true self. August Wilson says “that everyone has his or her own song. We must discover our songs.” This implies that everyone has their own unique ability, and that we must discover what makes us the most passionate in this life based on our own ability. Everyone has their own song they like as well and if you play the piano maybe you will come up with your own tune that you and other people will enjoy. 
					</p>
					<img src="https://www.obamaeagle.org/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/August_Wilson.jpg" id="aWilson">	
					<center>(August Wilson)</center>
			
					<h3>The House on Mango Street</h3>
					<p>In the “House on Mango Street” written by Sandra Cisneros, I enjoyed several chapters of the book. The three chapters I liked the most were “My Name”, “Laughter” and “Those Who Don't". The main themes throughout this book portray culture, identity and stereotypes. Throughout the book Esperanza is constantly on the search for self identity. She is forced to move into a crowded Latino neighborhood in Chicago. There is racial segregation in this area and she starts discovering her true self. In the chapter “My Name” she talks about how she wants a different name and why it means so much to her. Later on in the book she hits puberty and both her grandfather and aunt pass away. This shows that she is maturing and how it affects her emotions as a maturing women. She learns about the true meaning of her life and sees how beautiful the world really is. These are exact examples of how she is trying to figure out her identity.</p>
